<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0226 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1958EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-Storm     04-01 0249</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Storm,0261</SECOND><HEAD>Wintry Storm Blankets Panhandle With Snow</HEAD><DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A spring blizzard hit the Texas andOklahoma panhandles on Friday, stranding motorists and knocking outpower in areas.   As much as 6 inches of snow blanketed some areas and up to 20inches were expected from the strong storm system that moved out ofthe southern Rockies across northeastern New Mexico, the NationalWeather Service said.   ``They're going to have a white Easter there,'' said weatherservice forecaster Larry Mooney in Norman, Okla., referring to ablizzard warning posted for the Oklahoma Panhandle.   Mary Anne Burdo, a Highway Patrol dispatcher at Guymon, Okla.,where a foot of snow had fallen by late Friday afternoon, saidwesternmost Cimmaron County ``is completely shut down.''   ``We have a lot of stranded motorists in town and on thehighways,'' said police dispatcher Susie Simmons in Dalhart, innorthwest Texas. She said a lot of the travelers were on their wayto ski resorts.   ``I guess they can cross-country ski here,'' she said.   At least two major highways were closed, U.S. 87 through Dalhartand U.S. 287 north of Stratford, because of blowing snow, theDepartment of Public Safety said.   Winds of up to 30 mph caused power outages from West Amarillo toDumas, authorities said.   Thunderstorms, some producing hail, also rumbled across Texasand Oklahoma Friday.   The weather service issued a flood and flash flood watch formuch of southeast Texas, including metropolitan Houston, Galveston,Beaumont and Port Arthur.</TEXT></DOC>